                <note rend="inline" type="source">150.071 Control/38</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Castle</hi>) <hi rend="italic">of a Conversation With the
                        German Ambassador</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Von Prittwitz</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-03">March 3,
                            1931</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The German Ambassador called this morning to leave the attached memorandum<note
                        n="29" xml:id="d675fn29">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra.</hi>
                    </note> concerning Senate Bills with regard to shipping. I told the Ambassador
                    that I thought there was comparatively little chance that either of these bills
                    would go through at the present session of Congress, but, of course, there was
                    always a danger. I told him that this Department was opposed to the bills in
                    their present form and that we had already signified to the appropriate people
                    in Congress our disapprobation. He said he realized we had done this, but that
                    he felt he would be derelict, the situation being as it is, not to bring the
                    matter once more to our attention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W[<hi rend="smallcaps">illiam</hi>] R. C[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >astle</hi>], <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
